nd House, EastChurch, Kent, England":"Eastchurch, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1250–1319":"about 1250–1319","1250–1313":"1250–1313","1250–1319":"1250–1319","1254–1281":"1254–1281","1281–1308":"1281–1308","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1234–Female":"1234–Deceased","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1259":"1259","1313":"1313","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","Abt 1281":"about 1281","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","1317":"1317","Minster, Sheppey, Kent":"Minster, Kent, England","Shurland House, Eastchurch, Kent, England":"Eastchurch, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Eastchurch, Kent, England":"Eastchurch, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Shurland House, Eastchurch, Kent":"Eastchurch, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Shurland House, EastChurch, Kent, England":"Eastchurch, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shurland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Sharland in Morchard Bishop (Devon). The origin of the placename is uncertain."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Shurland was born about 1250, in Eastchurch, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Geoffrey de Shurland, was 52 and his mother, Marjory de Kent, was 17. He had at least 1 daughter with Margery. He died in 1319, in his hometown, at the age of 70, and was buried in Minster, Kent, England."},"et":{"Abt 1250–1319":"umbes 1250–1319","1250–1313":"1250–1313","1250–1319":"1250–1319","1254–1281":"1254–1281","1281–1308":"1281–1308","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1234–Female":"1234–Surnud","1250":"1250","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1259":"1259","1313":"1313","1234":"1234","1200":"1200","1254":"1254","Abt 1281":"umbes 1281","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","1317":"1317","Minster, Sheppey, Kent":"Minster, Kent, England","Shurland Hou